"Yes, boss. They must be on their way now; we gave them time to get provisions at the mess hall." At exactly 5:00, Company Exodus was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began speaking.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We need to support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the uprising. From there, we will have an advanced position and a foothold at the base of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units and board up."
The company dispersed, with each man joining his unit, and the sergeants ordered them onto the tanks. Cohren climbed into one of the armored vehicles, positioning himself at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, his legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat microphone.
"Cohren, does Harris always have Snowball?" Nemic asked as they settled in.
"Do you mean the chicken he stole?" Cohen remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure about that."
Cohren glanced towards one of the tanks and saw Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken bobbing its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he's always got it," Cohren replied as the turret of the tank opened with a clatter to let his commander pass through.
"All the tanks were on the move," the commander declared calmly but clearly through his helmet. The engines of a tank platoon and Stryker vehicles roared as they began to advance. The tank on which Cohren was riding jolted when its brakes were released and it started moving to form up. The tanks deployed in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. Winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud remained.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the beginning of the war, haven't you?"
"Yep, Storm of Fire operation," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd be able to handle it in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a mild way to put it," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we had anticipated. They managed to bring down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Damn, we should be seeing them from where we are."
"Well, I'll hold my ground for the Federation," said Orson somewhat provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You're saying that now, but from experience, I know that new recruits like you, who are 18 years old, take cover as soon as they hear gunfire," declared Craith.
"I think we won't have to wait long," said Corhen with a laugh. Orson did not continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," sizzled Cohren's radio. "We're detecting thermal signatures about 300 meters away, 20 degrees right."
Cohen climbed to the top of the chariot and put on his optical glasses. By activating the thermal vision, he was able to see thermal signatures in the distance.
" Yup, I see them," replied Cohren through his throat microphone.
"Enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Impossible to say," declared Cohren. He activated his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, do not shoot unless you are shot at, let's get them out."
